\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Voices may drop out early and enter late \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 In all the examples we have seen so far, the time values of all the notes in a given voice in a given bar add up to the number of beats in the bar.  However, in multivoice music, it is common for voices to enter partway through a bar without specifying leading rests, and to dropout before the end of a bar is reached without specifying trailing rests.  This notational shorthand is most commonly found in orchestral reductions onto a grand staff, in which it would be pointless and confusing to be required to specify leading and trailing rests for each part.  To a lesser extent this shorthand is found also in keyboard music.  Here are some examples of `early dropout':\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_15.eps \width9020\height3100
}¬} \par
