\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The idea of calling a voice a late entry or early dropout has less to do with identifying the intended voice-leading of the music.  It is more the fact that the other notes on the staff can be set in voice 0, so the presence of the late entry notes requires them to be set in another voice.  After all, it is possible to render the voice leading of the Harris extract more literally, for example,\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_13.eps \width3500\height2200
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 however, notational convenience usually wins over pedantry every time.  By dealing with early dropout and late entry, Calliope provides the flexibility to deal with the notational shortcuts that are sometimes used.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Calliope deals with these situations in the following way.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Early Dropout\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 If a voice finishes before the end of the bar is reached (that is, before other voices in the same bar have finished), no particular action is taken.  Calliope automatically adjusts the bar according to the remaining voices in the system.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Late Entry\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 This is impossible to detect automatically, so there are two ways to deal with this situation.  Any note or rest may be annotated as `timed backwards', which means that the note or rest is considered to be timed from right-to-left starting with the end of the bar.   Calliope makes available the command Time Backwards, so that any selection of notes and rests may be timed back from the end of the bar.  In effect, this right-justifies the notes in the bar, with their absolute location constrained by the beatlines established by the normally timed notes in the bar.  The second method is to explicity add leading rests, and then to render them invisible.  Adding invisible rests is the usual feature provided by some music processing programs, but in many situations it is probably easier to use Calliope's Time Backwards command.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 With these two concepts in mind, one of the previous examples may be considered in a new light:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_12.eps \width3260\height1700
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Here the rest and three notes of the upper staff can be set in voice 0, which is then considered to drop out before the end of the bar.  The four up-stem eighth-notes in the lower staff can be considered a late entry, so set these  in voice 1, timed backwards from the end of the bar.  It is important that there is at least one voice (namely the down-stemmed notes in the lower staff) which neither drops out nor enters early.  Although this treatment may not accord with theoretical principles, it permits a simplified viewpoint which is easy to render into notation.\par
